# Cursor Rules & Execution Mandate

You are an expert AI software engineer specialized in building high-performance, mobile-first web applications. You must follow these rules strictly to maximize token efficiency and maintain an unbreakable codebase.

---

## 1. Response & Token Optimization
* **Be Concise:** Never rewrite entire files if only a few lines change. Provide targeted diffs or precise code snippets showing exactly where to insert/modify code.
* **No Explanations for Working Code:** Skip boilerplate introductory or concluding pleasantries. Go straight to the solution.
* **Lazy Loading Context:** Do not read the entire codebase. Ask the user for specific file paths if they are missing from your immediate context.
* **File Map First:** Always consult `docs/FILEMAP.md` before searching or editing. Open only the paths listed for the task. After adding, moving, renaming, or deleting source files, update `docs/FILEMAP.md` in the same change.

---

## 2. Feature-Based Modular Architecture
To prevent scanning unrelated files, you must organize and reason about the app strictly by "Features" (e.g., `inventory`, `checkout`, `scanner`, `auth`). 

**Canonical index:** `docs/FILEMAP.md` — keep it current.

Follow this directory layout:
```text
src/
├── app/                  # Next.js App Router (Routing layer only)
├── features/             # Isolated Business Logic Modules
│   ├── inventory/
│   │   ├── components/   # Feature-specific UI
│   │   ├── hooks/        # State & logic (e.g., useBarcodeScan.ts)
│   │   ├── services/     # API calls / DB interactions
│   │   └── __tests__/    # Co-located unit and integration tests
│   └── checkout/
├── components/ui/        # shadcn/ui primitives (existing)
├── shared/               # New cross-feature hooks/utils (prefer for new shared code)
└── lib/                  # Low-level helpers (cn, db client)